Objective: In this lab, you will practice using Python's basic concepts such as data types, variables, operators, if else statements, loops, and functions.
Tasks:
Data Types:
a. Create a variable num1 and assign it the value 5.
b. Create a variable num2 and assign it the value 3.14.
c. Create a variable string1 and assign it the value "Hello, world!".
d. Print the values of the variables num1, num2, and string1.
e. Create a variable bool1 and assign it the value True.
f. Create a variable bool2 and assign it the value False.
g. Print the values of the variables bool1 and bool2.
Variables:
a. Create a variable name and assign it the value "John".
b. Create a variable age and assign it the value 30.
c. Print a message that says "My name is John and I am 30 years old." using the variables name and age.
Operators:
a. Create a variable num3 and assign it the value 10.
b. Create a variable num4 and assign it the value 3.
c. Print the result of adding num3 and num4.
d. Print the result of subtracting num3 and num4.
e. Print the result of multiplying num3 and num4.
f. Print the result of dividing num3 by num4.
g. Print the remainder of dividing num3 by num4.
h. Print the result of num3 raised to the power of num4.
If else statements:
a. Create a variable num5 and assign it the value 8.
b. Write an if else statement that checks if num5 is greater than 10. If it is, print "Num5 is greater than 10". Otherwise, print "Num5 is less than or equal to 10".
Loops:
a. Use a for loop to print the numbers from 1 to 5.
b. Use a while loop to print the numbers from 1 to 5.
Functions:
a. Define a function called square that takes one parameter x and returns the square of x.
b. Define a function called factorial that takes one parameter n and returns the factorial of n.
c. Call the square function with the argument 5 and print the result.
d. Call the factorial function with the argument 5 and print the result.

Instructions:
Save your code as a Python file with a .py extension.
Make sure your code runs without any errors.
